figuring out what causes
it and identifying the
risk factors and to

44:27.733 --> 44:29.400 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
really better understand it.

44:29.400 --> 44:32.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Help
us understand what
CTE does to the brain.

44:32.966 --> 44:37.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL ALOSCO: It's a
neurodegenerative disease,
so a neurodegenerative
disease similar to

44:37.600 --> 44:42.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Alzheimer's, but it's
very distinct from
Alzheimer's disease.

44:42.066 --> 44:45.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
What we see in CTE is
this protein called tau.

44:45.266 --> 44:50.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Tau is a protein that helps
stabilize the cell, but in
CTE, it becomes abnormal.

44:52.066 --> 44:56.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And, specifically, it
starts to collect around
the blood vessels.

44:56.600 --> 45:01.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's located at the base of
the (INAUDIBLE) kind of right
below the bottom of the tissue

45:03.600 --> 45:05.800 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of the brain.

45:05.800 --> 45:08.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And it's a really
unique presentation.

45:08.200 --> 45:11.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, Michael,
I know you sent us a slide.

45:11.400 --> 45:13.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We're going to put
that on the screen.

45:13.433 --> 45:16.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
